post_text:
Danaya Pollard Day is today! Help us to celebrate our UP 2020 senior by leaving her a message in the comments.

Mr. Kelley says:
Over the last several years I have watched as Danaya has transformed from a shy quiet student who sat in the back of the room and hardly said a word, to a young adult who is not afraid to speak her mind and yet does it in a respectful manner. One thing that has not changed is her desire to succeed, and succeed at a high level. Danaya continued to challenge herself, taking the “hard classes”, though sometimes hesitant in her answers, only because she never wanted to be wrong. Danaya has grown into a young adult that is passionate about her ideas, grades, future, and most importantly her love for all things chocolate.

Danaya, I am very sorry that you and the senior class missed out on an exciting 4th quarter, but more importantly being able to get the Reese's and Hershey Bar that was promised to you. I know whatever you decide to do in the future, you will be great. Continue to stay determined, passionate, and positively opinionated.

post_text:
Please join us as we celebrate Ronjanae Stevens Day at Urban Pathways! Leave a message for Ronjanae in the comments.

Mrs. Kelley says:

When I think of Ronjanae I think of someone with wisdom and maturity beyond her years. Every time Ronjane speaks, she speaks with impact. There is deep thought and wisdom behind her words whether in class or outside of class. Although I had Ronjanae in English class, it was outside of the classroom where I would truly see her shine. She always sees the good in people, and I think that makes her kind. If someone was struggling, she would be there. If someone ever needed a real talk, she was there. If someone just needed a friend, she was there. And if someone was being picked on, you better believe that she was there. Ronjane knows this world is bigger than her, but that she can have an immense effect on the people in it. Her kindness has no limit. In this crazy world there are just some people who are good, and she is one of them!

post_text:
O'Sha Stanford Day is today! Celebrate by sharing your pride and joy for O'Sha in the comments.

Ms. Beck says:
I can’t even count the number of times I’ve told O’Sha how proud of her I am. If you knew who she was compared to who she is today, you would be proud too. I’ve seen O’Sha grow and mature and overcome all the drama and negativity she once easily engaged in. Today, she stands out as a leader and is willing to give advice to younger students she sees herself in. She recognizes them heading down that same path and shares her own experiences. I know O’Sha is interested in a career in business or maybe real estate, but I do hope she considers opportunities to be involved with youth and continues to be a mentor for young boys and girls.

O’Sha, I appreciate you always being respectful towards me. I thank you for your kindness and wanting to help. Although you’re not heading into news reporting like I always predicted due to your nosiness and knowing all the tea, I know you will be great at whatever you do. Again, I am proud of you and Congratulations!

post_text:
Urban Pathways is celebrating our Class of 2020 today with Jeneba Bah Day! Leave a comment for Jeneba with well wishes and good memories.

Mrs. Akhand says:
When I first met you, you were very quiet and wouldn’t say much to me. I’m not sure if it was because you were shy or didn’t know how to take me. You decided to take Spanish and there is where we connected. I learned that you have a great sense of humor. I will always remember you asking “Why?!” whenever I would ask you something. You strive for your best and never give up. Keep your dedication to yourself and your family. I wish you all the best! Congratulations!

Today is Quent'en Lowry Day! Join us each day as we continue our celebration of the UP Class of 2020. Please leave well wishes and memories for Quent'en in the comments.

Mrs. Kalkhof (Ms. Clairise) says:

Dear Quent’en,

I want to start off by saying how proud I am of you. You have really broken out of your shell and seeing you grow as a student has been a joy for me. You are incredibly compassionate and hard-working. Thank you for all that you do and for all that you are. I’ll never forget bonding over Three Days Grace and Anime. Please take this time to celebrate your accomplishments because you deserve to! This is your time to shine and to be proud of what you have done. Congratulations Quent'en, you did it!

post_text:
UPCS 6-12 is celebrating the Class of 2020! Today is Mahogany Young Day! Post your good wishes and thoughts for Mahogany in the comments.

Mrs. Kelley says:
There are so many words that come to mind as I try to describe Mahogany Young. She is kind and treats all individuals with respect, even when no one else does. She is a student leader who can make any class discussion gain depth and become memorable. She is brave. She says what needs to be said, not what you want to hear. Finally, Mahogany is unforgettable. She is a stand out student who will continue to be a trailblazer in her future. I could go on and on about words that describe Mahogany, but alas, I only have a small paragraph. I am confident that in the future Mahogany will prove true everything I have said, and more. Mahogany, I felt so lucky to have you as a student. My hope for you is that your classroom be filled with students just as amazing as you! You are a bright student with a bright future. Best of luck out there Mahogany. Urban Pathways was lucky to have you as a student.

We are SO proud of these students for their hard work and dedication!

If you're interested in being part of the Interact Club, learn more for the 2019-2020 school year: http://bit.ly/2J9SO0G
shared_text:
Rotary Club of Pittsburgh
June 23, 2019 at 2:33 PM ·

Working with nonprofits in our community is how we put service above ourselves! One of those nonprofits is the Interact Club at Urban Pathways 6-12 Charter School!

This club brings students (ages 12-18) together to develop their leadership skills and connect with community leaders through fun and interactive events. The students work to make a difference at school and in the community, work on projects that benefit Urban Pathways, Pittsburgh, and the world, develop leadership skills, and have fun and create new friendships!

Thank you, Urban Pathways, for all the work you do and the difference you make in these students lives!

post_text: Dear parents and guardians - Urban Pathways 6-12 Charter School will be closed and all school activities are canceled on Thursday, May 23rd and Friday, May 24th after being alerted by law enforcement of an alleged threat. April 9, 2019 at 4:18 PM ·

Today, high school students from Mt. Lebanon School District, Woodland Hills Jr/Sr High School, Urban Pathways 6-12 Charter School and Pittsburgh CAPA in Pittsburgh are participating in Minority Law Day, an educational event presented by the PBA Minority Bar Committee. The day's topic is the First Amendment & how it applies to students.
